Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election (10) saw the victory of several pro-Western parties, including the People's Front and Self-Help (3,4). However, the Opposition Bloc, which included allies of former President Yanukovych, also gained a significant percentage of votes (2,4). This party had distanced itself from the Yanukovych era and saw a boost in its rating (1). The election also marked a step towards Ukraine's potential membership in NATO (8). However, oligarchs were seen to consolidate their power following the election (9). The mixed proportional-simple plurality system used in the election posed challenges for some districts, particularly in secessionist regions (10).

Timeline.Text: Opposition Bloc distances itself from the Yanukovych era, boosting its popularity in the lead-up to the Ukrainian parliamentary election.
Ukraine overwhelmingly elects pro-Western parties in the parliamentary election.
The Opposition Bloc, including allies of former president Viktor Yanukovych, receives 9.2% of the votes in the Ukrainian parliamentary election.
Oligarchs consolidate power in Ukraine after the parliamentary election.
The 8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada begins its term, with 421 people's deputies elected during the 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election.
The Ukrainian Parliament votes to take steps towards joining NATO.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election took place on October 26, 2014 (3,4,8,10). It was called for by President Petro Poroshenko after his victory in the presidential elections in May (3). Pro-Western parties were expected to win (2) and the election was seen as a win for democracy (5). However, right-wing nationalist parties also made gains (9). The Communist Party of Ukraine did not perform well, with its political landscape changing (1). The election was boycotted by many and seen as deepening existing divisions in the country (7,9).

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election (6) resulted in a coalition agreement between pro-Western parties (9) and a victory for right-wing nationalist parties (3,7). The People's Front Party, the Bloc of Petro Poroshenko, the Samopomich Union, the Opposition Bloc, Oleh Liashko's Radical Party, and the Batkivschyna All-Ukrainian Union were among the parties that won seats in the Verkhovna Rada (1,2,4,10). The Petro Poroshenko bloc and the People's Front Party control the most seats (2).

Timeline.Text: The Central Election Commission announces the official results of the 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election, showing that Oleh Liashko's Radical Party has passed the 5% threshold.
Ukraine's parliamentary parties initial a coalition agreement, indicating that Oleh Liashko's Radical Party will have 22 seats in the new parliament.
The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election takes place, with several right-wing nationalist parties, including Oleh Liashko's Radical Party, achieving victories.
The snap parliamentary elections are held, with Oleh Liashko's Radical Party competing as a relatively new party.
The results of the parliamentary election show that Oleh Liashko's Radical Party and other previously obscure parties have gained significant support.
A survey shows that Oleh Liashko's Radical Party is expected to win 12.9% of the vote in the upcoming parliamentary election.

The first results of the parliamentary elections show a victory for pro-Western parties.
The far-right party Right Sector receives only 1.6% of the vote in the parliamentary elections.
Ukraine's new parliament sits for the first time, with several members from right-wing nationalist parties.
The OSCE/ODIHR opens an election observation mission for the early parliamentary elections in Ukraine.
Pro-European parties are expected to win a solid majority of seats in the upcoming parliamentary elections in Ukraine.
Several Ukraine officials from Right Sector are found dumped in wheelie bins.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election occurred on October 26 (2, 6) and was a milestone for the Ukrainian people (1). The United States congratulated the candidates and voters (1), and President Petro Poroshenko had pressed for early elections since his victory in the presidential elections (2). The elections were held to elect members of the Verkhovna Rada (2). The policies of the new Parliament were discussed (5) and the OSCE stated that the elections were "free and fair" (10). Pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine also held presidential and parliamentary elections on November 2 (9).

Timeline.Text: The United States congratulates the thousands of candidates and millions of voters in Ukraine on the parliamentary elections.
Snap parliamentary elections are held in Ukraine, with President Petro Poroshenko pressing for early elections.
Pro-Russian separatist elections in eastern Ukraine on November 2 are controversial.
The Hromadske International team produces the Sunday Show, explaining the Eastern Ukraine conflict.
The People's Front Party, led by Ukrainian Prime Minister Arseny Yatsenyuk, wins the parliamentary election.
A first-time voter is unimpressed by the parliamentary candidates vying for her vote.
Ukraine's parliamentary elections are held on October 26.
Election monitors from the OSCE declare Ukraine's parliamentary elections as 'free and fair'.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election saw a number of new faces in parliament, including members of the Samopomich party (3,4,6). Andriy Parubiy of the People's Front party was elected as the first vice speaker, with Oksana Syroid of the Samopomich Union party as the deputy speaker (2). The election was seen as a triumph for pro-European parties, with Samopomich coming in third with 14% of the vote (6). The party's leader, Andriy Sadovyy, spoke about his plans for building a functioning Ukrainian government (3). Russia stated that they would recognize the election results (10).

Timeline.Text: Parliamentary election in Ukraine deepens existing divides, including those related to the Samopomich party.
In the parliamentary election, pro-European parties, including the newly-formed Samopomich party, are leading in the polls.
The parliamentary election in Ukraine is recognized by Russia, with the People's Front and Samopomich party gaining significant support.
Andriy Sadovyy, leader of the Samopomich party, discusses plans for building a functioning government in Ukraine.
The parliamentary election in Ukraine is hailed as a win for democracy, with many reformists and newcomers gaining seats, including members of the Samopomich party.
Oksana Syroid, a member of the Samopomich party, is elected as deputy speaker of the Verkhovna Rada.
A list of members of the new Verkhovna Rada is released, including 421 people's deputies elected during the 2014 parliamentary elections, including members of the Samopomich party.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election saw pro-Western parties dominate and open coalition talks (3,5,7). The All-Ukrainian Batkivshchyna Association, led by Yulia Tymoshenko, was one of the principal parties in the election (1,10). Sixteen candidates running for the Internet Party of Ukraine, including six Darth Vaders, were registered to run in the election (4,9). The 8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada, which began its term in 2014, had 421 elected members (2). The election also showed strong opposition to Russian aggression and support for the Kyiv government (6).

Timeline.Text: Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko hosts a first round of coalition talks after early results show that pro-Western parties have won the parliamentary elections, including the All-Ukrainian Batkivshchyna (Fatherland) Association.
Ukraine holds successful parliamentary elections, demonstrating the country's commitment to an inclusive and transparent political process.
Pro-Western parties are expected to dominate Ukraine's parliament, giving President Petro Poroshenko a mandate to steer the country further away from Russia.
The United States congratulates Ukraine on its successful parliamentary elections and praises the country's commitment to a transparent political process.
Ukraine's 8th Verkhovna Rada begins its term with 421 elected members, including members from the All-Ukrainian Batkivshchyna (Fatherland) Association.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election focused on the Verkhovna Rada (1,2). The election, which was held on October 26, 2014, was called for by President Petro Poroshenko after the July breakup of the ruling coalition (2). Over 40% of eligible voters participated in the election (6). The People's Front party, founded by Arseniy Yatsenyuk and Oleksandr Turchynov, gained 12 seats in the Verkhovna Rada (4,5). President Poroshenko addressed the Verkhovna Rada on November 27, 2014, emphasizing the need for cooperation between the Parliament and the President in order to achieve the desired results for the people of Ukraine (8). The election results were seen as a victory for democracy and for President Poroshenko and Prime Minister Yatsenyuk (9,10).

Timeline.Text: Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko announces early parliamentary elections.
Ukrainians vote in parliamentary elections, with a turnout over 40%.
Russia recognizes the results of the Ukrainian parliamentary elections.
The Verkhovna Rada votes to abandon neutrality and seek NATO membership.
The nationalist and conservative party People's Front is founded in Ukraine.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko addresses the Verkhovna Rada, emphasizing the need for cooperation and reformatory efforts.
The European Parliament and the Verkhovna Rada ratify a political and trade agreement between the European Union and Ukraine.
The People's Front party wins seats in the Verkhovna Rada during the parliamentary elections.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko and Prime Minister Arseniy Yatsenyuk claim victory in the parliamentary elections.

Overview.Summary: According to exit polls, the ultra-nationalist party Svoboda captured around six percent of the vote (1). However, it had lost its image as the most radical player in parliamentary politics and no longer had the possibility of repeating its success from 2012 (2). The 8th Ukrainian Verkhovna Rada, elected in 2014, includes members from Svoboda (4). The party is known for its links to neo-Nazism (7). The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election was seen as a win for democracy and a drift away from Russia (3,5).

Timeline.Text: Ukrainian voters overwhelmingly back pro-Western parties in the parliamentary elections.
The far-right party Svoboda experiences a significant drop in voter support compared to previous elections.
The results of the parliamentary election are seen as a win for democracy in Ukraine.
The remnants of the former ruling party, Party of Regions, have been renamed as the Opposition Bloc and are now the smallest faction in parliament.
President Poroshenko's pro-Western party is expected to secure a parliamentary majority in the election.
The Ukrainian parliament is inaugurated for its new term with 421 elected members.

Overview.Summary:
The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election had various events and incidents surrounding it, including protests and demonstrations. One aspect of the election was the involvement of the Ukrainian political party, "Svoboda," which appealed to society with drafted bills for every point of their election program (8). In November 2014, Czech Republic and Slovakia celebrated the 25th anniversary of the "Velvet Revolution" (7). In September of the same year, deputy of the Lviv regional council and member of the All-Ukrainian Union "Svoboda" Irina Fahrion was in a depressive state (4). In August, the party organized a second group to be sent to the East (9). In July, the war in Donbass continued (5,6). In June, Czech Republic and Slovakia celebrated 25 years since the beginning of the "Velvet Revolution" (7). In November 2014, the successful young organist Pavel Svoboda founded the International Music Festival F. L. Věk and became its artistic director (10). In December 2014, the people's deputy of the seventh convocation, Irina Fahrion, was in a very depressive state (4). The party "Svoboda" was also mentioned in relation to a creation of light in November (1). The aspect of the party's involvement in the election was also mentioned in articles from December (2,3). 

=== End of Summary ===

Timeline.Text: Oleh Tiahnybok of the all-ukrainian union "svoboda" appeals to society with drafted bills for every point of their election programme.
Pavel Svoboda, a successful young organist, founds the international F. L. Věk festival and becomes its artistic director.
The 25th anniversary of the beginning of the 'velvet revolution' is marked by the Czech Republic and Slovakia.
EthanC2H6 uses Svoboda lights for a creation and notes their perfect functioning when at 20% power.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election was held on October 26 (1,2,3,5,8,10). President Petro Poroshenko had pressed for early parliamentary elections since his victory in the presidential elections in May (3). The ruling coalition government collapsed in July, giving Poroshenko the right to dissolve parliament (5). Pro-Western parties won an overwhelming majority, with Poroshenko's bloc taking a razor-thin lead (7,8). Poroshenko also called for assistance from the US Congress in the fight against rebels (4). The election was seen as a step toward stability for Ukraine (10).

Timeline.Text: Ukrainian voters prepare to elect a new parliament, as requested by President Petro Poroshenko.
President Poroshenko launches an anti-corruption drive ahead of the parliamentary election.
Ukrainians are set to vote in a parliamentary election that could bring stability to the country.
Pro-Western parties win the majority in Ukraine's parliamentary election, as confirmed by President Poroshenko.
The initial counting process for the parliamentary election shows a close race between Prime Minister Arseny Yatsenyuk's People's Front and the political bloc supporting President Poroshenko.
President Poroshenko calls for the reinforcement of key cities in case of rebel attacks.
Ukrainian President Poroshenko asks Congress for military support in the fight against rebels.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election saw pro-Western parties win and reaffirm their support for European ideals (4,6,10). Many candidates and millions of voters campaigned for this election (1). The United States and the European Union hailed it as a victory for democracy (7). Sixteen Darth Vaders also ran for parliamentary seats as part of the Internet Party of Ukraine (3,9). The election was seen as a milestone for the Ukrainian people (1) and a rejection of far-right ideologies (4).

Timeline.Text: The Internet Party of Ukraine, which includes several Star Wars characters, announces its list of candidates for the parliamentary election.
The United States congratulates the thousands of candidates and millions of voters in Ukraine who have campaigned for the parliamentary election.
Exit polls show that pro-Western parties have overwhelmingly won the Ukrainian parliamentary election.
President Petro Poroshenko says the projected outcome of the parliamentary election shows strong support for Ukraine's path to Europe.
The United States and European Union hail the parliamentary election in Ukraine as a victory for democracy.
Human Rights Watch reports evidence of Ukraine attacking populated areas.
Russia and separatist representatives sign an agreement in Minsk, Belarus, for legitimate local elections to be held in parts of Donetsk and Luhansk.

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election, held on October 26, was a win for pro-democracy parties (6). The election was a response to the dissolution of the ruling coalition government by President Petro Poroshenko (3). It was boycotted by the majority of the electorate (1) and deepened the divide in eastern Ukraine (2). Pro-Western parties dominated the election (8) and the results were deemed free and fair by the OSCE election monitors (10).

Timeline.Text: Ukrainian voters head to the ballot box to elect a new parliament.
The parliamentary election in eastern Ukraine deepens the divide in the country.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko dissolves parliament and calls for early elections.
Snap parliamentary elections are held in Ukraine to elect members of the Verkhovna Rada.
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe declares the parliamentary elections in Ukraine to be 'free and fair'.
Arseniy Yatsenyuk is confirmed as prime minister of Ukraine by the Ukrainian parliament.

The People's Front party, founded by members of Fatherland (4), was one of the pro-Western parties that won seats in the election (2). The election was seen as a win for democracy (10).

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election (event) resulted in a win for pro-Western parties (1,5,6). These parties formed the "European Ukraine" coalition, which included the Self Reliance political party (2). The work of the new parliament started on November 27, 2014 with the establishment of official results (2). The election date was October 26, 2014 (3). The Petro Poroshenko Bloc was expected to win the majority of seats, but would not have a parliamentary majority without forming a coalition with other parties (8). The competitive political parties had the right to register their candidates until September 16, 2014, while self-nominated candidates could submit their applications until September 26, 2014 (9). There was disagreement whether a new government should be formed before the parliamentary elections (10).

Overview.Summary: The 2014 Ukrainian parliamentary election was held on October 26, 2014 and resulted in a victory for pro-Western parties (15). The ruling coalition government collapsed, leading to the dissolution of parliament by President Petro Poroshenko and calling for early elections (8, 12). The All-Ukrainian Batkivshchyna (Fatherland) Association, led by Yulia Tymoshenko, was one of the principal political parties in Ukraine (14). The work of the new parliament started on November 27, 2014 and a coalition was formed by five factions (16). Five parties managed to clear the 5% threshold in the snap elections: Petro Poroshenko Bloc, People's Front, Self Reliance, Radical Party, and Fatherland (13). The official results of the election were announced on November 10, 2014 (13). The election was seen as a win for democracy in Ukraine (19).

Timeline.Text: Ukraine signs an agreement with the European Union to deepen economic and political ties.
The United States congratulates the thousands of candidates and millions of voters in Ukraine who have campaigned in the country's parliamentary election.
Regular elections are held in Ukraine for the Verkhovna Rada.
Nationalism emerges as the winner in the Ukrainian parliamentary elections.
The political landscape changes but conflict remains with hardliners Yatsenyuk and Turchynov's People's Front polling well.
The Central Election Commission announces the official results of the Rada election.
The second Yatsenyuk government is approved.
